ReportDescription: Has the table so only can produce 4000 assessments with data un-cached

11.Name: all_assessments
11.SqlCommand:
SELECT 
    a.id AS [assessid],
    a.woundFk AS [woundid], 
    a.patientFk AS [patientid],
    a.createdByUserName AS [Created By],
    CONCAT(p.firstName, ' ', p.lastName) AS [Patient Name],
    u.name AS [Unit Name],
    LEFT(u.name, 2) AS [state Name],
    d.date AS [Assessment Date], -- Fetch date from the dimdate table
    w.description AS [Wound Description]
FROM 
    rpt.assessment a
INNER JOIN 
    rpt.patient p ON a.patientFk = p.id
INNER JOIN 
    rpt.unit u ON a.unitFk = u.id
INNER JOIN 
    rpt.dimdate d ON a.dimdateFk = d.id -- Link dimdateFk to the id column in dimdate
INNER JOIN 
    rpt.wound w ON w.id=a.woundFk
LEFT JOIN 
    rpt.AssessmentTypeVersion atv ON a.assessmentTypeVersionFk = atv.id -- Join with AssessmentTypeVersion
LEFT JOIN 
    rpt.AttributeType atr ON atr.name = 'Primary Etiology' -- Join with AttributeType for primary etiology
WHERE 
    atv.name = 'Wound Assessment' -- Filter for "Wound Assessment"
    AND LEFT(u.name, 2) != 'Te' -- Corrected comparison operator for SQL Server
ORDER BY 
    d.date DESC -- Sort using the date from dimdate
OFFSET 0 ROWS FETCH NEXT 12000 ROWS ONLY; -- Correct syntax for OFFSET-FETCH in SQL Server

13.Name: working_weekly_data
13.SqlCommand:
-- Step 1: Determine the range of years directly using the dimdate table and assessment table
WITH YearRange AS (
    SELECT 
        MIN(DATEPART(YEAR, d.date)) AS EarliestYear, 
        MAX(DATEPART(YEAR, d.date)) AS LatestYear
    FROM 
        rpt.dimdate d
    WHERE 
        d.id = (SELECT MIN(a.dimDateFk) FROM rpt.assessment a)
)

-- Step 2: Generate week series using CTEs
, WeekSeries AS (
    SELECT 
        DATEPART(YEAR, d.date) AS Year,
        DATEPART(WEEK, d.date) AS Week
    FROM 
        rpt.dimdate d
    CROSS JOIN YearRange yr -- Join with YearRange CTE
    WHERE 
        DATEPART(YEAR, d.date) BETWEEN yr.EarliestYear AND yr.LatestYear
    GROUP BY 
        DATEPART(YEAR, d.date), DATEPART(WEEK, d.date)
)

-- Step 3: Get all users
, AllUsers AS (
    SELECT DISTINCT 
        a.createdByUserName
    FROM 
        rpt.assessment a
)

-- Step 4: Generate week-user combinations
, WeekUserCombination AS (
    SELECT 
        ws.Year,
        ws.Week,
        au.createdByUserName AS UserName
    FROM 
        WeekSeries ws
    CROSS JOIN 
        AllUsers au
)

-- Step 5: Aggregate weekly data
, WeeklyData AS (
    SELECT 
        DATEPART(YEAR, a.date) AS Year,
        DATEPART(WEEK, a.date) AS Week,
        a.createdByUserName AS UserName,
        COUNT(DISTINCT CASE 
                          WHEN atv.name = 'Wound Assessment' THEN a.id 
                          ELSE NULL 
                      END) AS AssessmentCount,
        COUNT(DISTINCT a.woundFk) AS WoundCount,
        COUNT(DISTINCT a.patientFk) AS PatientCount
    FROM 
        rpt.assessment a
    INNER JOIN 
        rpt.AssessmentTypeVersion atv
        ON a.assessmentTypeVersionFk = atv.id
    WHERE 
        DATEPART(YEAR, a.date) BETWEEN (SELECT EarliestYear FROM YearRange) AND (SELECT LatestYear FROM YearRange)
    GROUP BY 
        DATEPART(YEAR, a.date), DATEPART(WEEK, a.date), a.createdByUserName
)

-- Step 6: Combine data
SELECT 
    wuc.Year,
    wuc.Week,
    wuc.UserName,
    ISNULL(wd.AssessmentCount, 0) AS AssessmentCount,
    ISNULL(wd.WoundCount, 0) AS WoundCount,
    ISNULL(wd.PatientCount, 0) AS PatientCount
FROM 
    WeekUserCombination wuc
LEFT JOIN 
    WeeklyData wd
    ON wuc.Year = wd.Year 
    AND wuc.Week = wd.Week 
    AND wuc.UserName = wd.UserName
ORDER BY 
    wuc.Year, wuc.Week, wuc.UserName;
